“Playing music is the best feeling in the world. As long as I can do that, I’ll be happy.” — Jason Barnes

Jason Barnes (@cybrnetx), a drummer and composer from Atlanta, lost his lower right arm after an electrical accident in 2012. Determined to continue pursuing music, Jason worked with a group of Georgia Tech researchers to create a custom, TensorFlow-powered drumming arm that lets him drum almost as naturally as with his own arm.

Meet Matthew. As someone who was born deaf, he usually relies on video chat and lip-reading to communicate with his son. But by using Live Caption* on his Google Pixel, Matthew made a phone call to his son for the first time in his life. #TrueStories

*English only. Available only on Pixel 2 or newer phones and select other Android phones. Accuracy of Live Caption depends on the quality and clarity of the audio source. Not applicable to music and not available on all media apps. See https://g.co/help/livecaption.

node.title: First Call With My Son — Matt’s True Story

node.text: Today's #GoogleDoodle celebrates swing dancing and the Savoy Ballroom in Harlem, NY. This iconic Swing Era ballroom made history as one of the first racially integrated public spaces in the U.S. when it opened its doors in 1926. Known as the “Home of Happy Feet,” the Savoy Ballroom is also where people first danced iconic dances like the Lindy Hop and the Mambo. Go behind the scenes of the making of today's Doodle and then (Lindy) hop on over to our homepage to test out your own swing dance moves in our multiplayer game.

Sometimes a world of adventures starts with a single search. When one dad turns to Google to cure his young son’s boredom, a new passion for octopuses takes hold. 🐙

After Chris and his family got into a car accident, his Google Pixel used car crash detection* to immediately call for help. This is his True Pixel Story. #TrueStories

*Available only on Pixel 3, 4, 4a, 4a (5G) and 5 phones. Not available in all languages or countries. Car crash detection may not detect all accidents. High-impact activities may trigger calls to emergency services. This feature is dependent upon network connectivity and other factors and may not be reliable for emergency communications or available in all areas. For more information see g.co/pixel/carcrashdetection

node.text:
“I’m grateful because not only am I playing music like I always wanted, I’m also helping to develop some of the best technology for amputees.” - Jason Barnes

Since he was young, Jason Barnes (@cybrnetx) has loved playing drums. This didn’t change when he lost his arm in an electrical accident at the age of 22. Almost a decade later, Jason’s passion has led to the co-creation of one of the world’s most advanced prosthetic limbs with TensorFlow. Learn more at the link in our bio. #GAAD #withusandforus

📷: @justinkaneps

Justin is a photographer based in New York City. “Living with a disability myself, I can empathize with Jason’s story and relate to the way one must adapt to a world built for those without these differences. I admire Jason’s tenacity, and I’m honored to help tell his story.”

[Image Description: Panel 1: Jason Barnes playing drums against a black backdrop. Panel 2: Jason Barnes in a classroom looking at a laptop. Panel 3: A closeup of Jason’s prosthetic arm with drumsticks on a wood table. Schematic drawings are on the wall in the background Panel 4: A portrait of Jason Barnes against a black backdrop. You can see his knuckle tattoos, which read, “life.”]
